[[File:Rubbing faux-fur, July 2014.jpg|thumb|right|x200px|alt=Hand rubbing faux-fur|Feeling soft or otherwise enjoyable textures is a common form of stimming.]] '''Self-stimulatory behavior''', also known as '''stimming'''<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.mk/books?id=7X4QAgAAQBAJ&dq=&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=An Asperger Leader's Guide to Living and Leading Change | publisher=[[Jessica Kingsley Publishers]] | author=Rosalind Bergemann | year=2013 | isbn=9780857008725}}</ref> and '''self-stimulation''',<ref name="Foley">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.mk/books?id=FGO8S2RmckEC&dq=&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=The Autism Experience | publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com | author=Valerie Foley | year=2011 | isbn=9781458797285}}</ref> is the repetition of physical movements, sounds, or words, or the repetitive movement of objects common in individuals with [[developmental disabilities]] and most prevalent in people with [[autism spectrum]] disorders.<ref name="Foley"/><ref name="Stephen">{{cite web | url=http://www.autism.com/symptoms_self-stim | title=Self-Stimulatory Behavior |date=| publisher=[[Autism Research Institute]] | author=Stephen M. Edelson, Ph.D.}}</ref> It is also commonly seen in people with [[Anxiety disorder|anxiety disorders]] such as [[obsessive–compulsive disorder]], [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADHD]], and [[Tourette syndrome]], and in people with [[neurological disorder]]s or brain infections.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://autism.lovetoknow.com/diagnosing-autism/is-stimming-always-autism|title=Is Stimming Always Autism? {{!}} LoveToKnow|work=LoveToKnow|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@honeybadgershike/stimming-adhd-tics-the-more-you-know-f8b9607f59d|title=Stimming, Tics & ADHD: The More You Know|last=Insights|first=TMI: Tourette Mama|date=2017-09-16|website=TMI: Tourette Mama Insights|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref> It is considered a protective response to over-stimulation, in which people calm themselves by blocking less predictable environmental stimuli, to which they have a heightened sensitivity.<ref name="Foley"/><ref name="Cowell">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.mk/books?id=JiBo8JYaBjIC&dq=&source=gbs_navlinks_s | title=Help for the Child with Asperger's Syndrome: A Parent's Guide to Negotiating the Social Service Maze | publisher=[[Jessica Kingsley Publishers]] | author=Gretchen Mertz Cowell | year=2004 | isbn=9781846420429}}</ref> [[Sensory processing disorder]] is also given as a reason by some therapists for the behavior.<ref name="Cowell"/> Another theory is that stimming is a way to relieve [[anxiety]] and other emotions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.healthcentral.com/autism/c/1443/141549/spectrum-disorders | title=Autism Spectrum Disorders and Anxiety | publisher=[[Health Central]] | date=15 July 2011 | accessdate=25 March 2014 | author=Eileen Bailey}}</ref>
Common stimming behaviors (sometimes called '''stims'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://autismdigest.com/why-do-kids-with-autism-stim/ | title=Why Do Kids with Autism Stim? | publisher=Autism Digest | date=November–December 2011 | accessdate=25 March 2014 | author=Temple Grandin, PhD | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331005808/http://autismdigest.com/why-do-kids-with-autism-stim/ | archivedate=31 March 2014 | df= }}</ref>) include hand flapping, rocking, excessive or hard blinking, pacing, head banging, repeating noises or words, snapping fingers, and spinning objects.<ref name="Stimming">{{cite web | url=http://www.healthcentral.com/autism/c/1443/155585/stimming/ | title=Stimming | publisher=[[Health Central]] | date=27 August 2012 | accessdate=25 March 2014 | author=Eileen Bailey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-ouch-22771894 | title=Stimming: What autistic people do to feel calmer | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=5 June 2013 | accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Stimming is almost always present in autism, but does not necessarily indicate its presence.<ref name="About">{{cite web | url=http://autism.about.com/od/autismterms/f/stimming.htm | title=Stimming | publisher=[[About.com]] | date=13 October 2009 | accessdate=24 March 2014 | author=Lisa Jo Rudy}}</ref> The biggest difference between autistic and non-autistic stimming is in the type of ''stim'' and the quantity of stimming.<ref name="About"/> When the need to stim or the amount of stimming interferes with normal behavior, it becomes diagnosable as autism, Asperger's or [[Sensory processing disorder|SPD]] (not recognized in the ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]''){{Citation needed |date=August 2018 |reason=The source cited does not mention diagnosis. Surely the presence of stimming alone isn't enough?}}.
In the ''Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders'', published by the [[American Psychiatric Association]], this type of behavior is described as "stereotyped and repetitive motor mannerisms" and listed as one of the symptoms of autism.<ref>“Autism Spectrum Disorders”, 1994, ''Diagnostic and Statistical Manual'', American Psychiatric Association</ref> There are numerous ways to reduce or eliminate [[stereotypic behavior]]s, including providing alternative forms of stimulation and the use of medication (however, it is not clear whether medication is actually beneficial or restricts the individual from finding relief).<ref name="Stephen"/> {{clarify |date=August 2018 |reason=This reads as though the drugs make the stimming behavior no longer relieving. Is that correct? If so, it should be explicitly stated; the parenthetical statement is vague as-is.}}
The majority of the autistic community opposes attempts to reduce or eliminate stimming, as it is an important tool for self-regulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autismwestmidlands.org.uk/upload/pdf_files/1420460949_stimming.pdf|title=Autism and Stimming|last=|first=|date=|website=Autism West Midlands|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607162718/http://www.autismwestmidlands.org.uk/upload/pdf_files/1420460949_stimming.pdf|archive-date=2015-06-07|dead-url=yes|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailydot.com/irl/stimtastic-jewelry-autistic/|title=Meet the company that's making jewelry for adults with autism {{!}} The Daily Dot|date=2016-07-20|work=The Daily Dot|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thecaffeinatedautistic.wordpress.com/2013/02/10/on-stimming-and-why-quiet-handsing-an-autistic-person-is-wrong/|title=On Stimming and why “quiet hands”ing an Autistic person is wrong|date=2013-02-10|work=The Caffeinated Autistic|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Many contend that attempts to stop people from stimming are potentially abusive. {{clarify |date=August 2018 |reason=What very basis?}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2016/08/aba-autism-controversy/495272/|title=Is the Most Common Therapy for Autism Cruel?|last=DeVita-Raeburn|first=Elizabeth|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://autismwomensnetwork.org/my-thoughts-on-aba/|title=My Thoughts on ABA - Autism Women's Network|date=2015-02-11|work=Autism Women's Network|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://spectrumnews.org/features/deep-dive/controversy-autisms-common-therapy/|title=The controversy over autism’s most common therapy {{!}} Spectrum {{!}} Autism Research News|date=2016-08-10|work=Spectrum {{!}} Autism Research News|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://madasbirdsblog.wordpress.com/2017/04/25/i-abused-children-and-so-do-you-a-response-to-an-aba-apologist/|title=I Abused Children And SO DO YOU: A Response To An ABA Apologist|date=2017-04-25|work=Diary Of A Birdmad girl|access-date=2017-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref>
Stimming can sometimes be [[self-injury|self-injurious]], such as when it involves head-banging, hand-biting, and excessive self-rubbing and scratching.<ref name="SIB">{{cite web | url=http://www.autism.com/symptoms_self-injury | title=Self-Injurious Behavior | publisher=[[Autism Research Institute]] | accessdate=29 March 2014 | author=Stephen M. Edelson, Ph.D.}}</ref> However, viewed through the lens of SPD and autism, these behaviours can be seen as an adaptive response to over- and underwhelming interpretation of sensory stimuli{{clarify |date=August 2018 |reason=Viewed through the lens of SPD and autism as in viewed from the perspective of a person who has those? Or viewed with a knowledge of those conditions? If the latter, in what way does that knowledge inform one's view of self-injurious stimming? Also, what are over- and underwhelming interpretations of sensory stimuli, and how is self-injurious stimming an adaptive response to them?}}
Stimming can sometimes be mistaken for a sign of drug abuse.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/autistic-teen-who-was-roughed-up-by-police-speaks-out/|title=Family of teen with autism mistakenly tackled by police calls for better training|date=September 21, 2017|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/cop-thought-it-was-drugs-it-was-a-teen-coping-with-autism-lawsuit|title=Cop Thought It Was Drugs. It Was a Teen Coping With Autism: Lawsuit|date=7 June 2018|author=Victoria Albert|publisher=The Daily Beast|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>
